The movement is also supported by two former American transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, called on Congress to move toward mileage accounting.
Last year, the US Senate approved a $90 million pilot project involving 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move, responding to the concerns of MPs from rural areas who represent people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or the city in their everyday lives.
Nevertheless, several states and large cities are moving in this direction on their own.
Oregon, currently recruiting 5,000 drivers to the country ’ s largest experiment, is most committed.
