Esa chooses major space missions: Missions for billions
Far planets, waves of gravity or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they intend to launch in the coming years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, five are still in the race.
Worlds.
More than 1000 planets in other stars have already found astronomers.
No one knows whether there are lives in at least some of them.
The choice is difficult: should look for gravitational waves?
Or rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for earth-like planets and thus perhaps discover extra-terrestrial life?
These are the very questions responsible for the European Space Agency, Esa, are asking.
For their Cosmic Vision programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects, which are intended to make decisive progress in research.
The budget for such' L missions' each is around EUR 1 billion.
The launch is expected to take place in 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were up for discussion, five of them have now been shortlisted.
Many bodies are examining the proposals and hasing researchers.
A final decision is due to be taken by the scientific programme committee in the next few days.
The Esa has selected a total of four major questions to which the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme, launched in 2007, should find answers.
What are the conditions for the creation of planets and lives?
The exact processes of forming stars from large gas clouds - and thus the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in the proverbial dark.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star owns planets, under what circumstances can life be created there?
To investigate this question, the Cheops space telescope is to be launched in 2017, which will examine more closely at 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity.
The possibilities are limited, however, and cheops is a small mission with a budget of EUR 150 million.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map earth-like planets, even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, searching for " biomarkers ": gases deemed to indicate biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately intended to shed light on the conditions for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field, as well as the particle radiation it emits with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be examined as an example.
With the Solar Orbiter, Esa has already approved an M class mission (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this issue.
The probe should start in 2017 and closely observe the surface and activity of the sun.
Jupiter and his moons are also of great interest to researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet has played in the development of the solar system.
The Esa provides for the first of the three L missions of the " Cosmic Vision " program.
The probe " Juice " (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to start its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reached Jupiter to examine the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons of Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
Space offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to check whether the laws of nature with which we know are still valid there.
There may also be discrepancies that could physicists in the way to a new theory under which umbrella of all known laws of nature can be combined.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago our cosmos arose by the big bang.
In addition to the matter we know, that makes up stars, planets, and living beings like us, there are dark matter whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies, and dark energy that accelerates the expansion of outer space.
So far, researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fraction of a second of the Big bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With " Euclid ", the Esa has already approved an M mission, which is scheduled to be launched in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to examine the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus enabling conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who Could the Race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection procedure.
In the opinion of many experts, the best chances of approval as an L-mission have " E-Lisa ", an ambitious concept for detecting gravitational waves.
This means physicists changes in the structure of spacestime that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proved to date.
Elisa could do that, scientists behind the project hope.
The mission provided with a detector consisting of two or three probes stationed in space.
Unlike facilities on Earth, it could also demonstrate gravitational waves created during the Big bang, providing new insights into the emergence of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are competing for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called " Athena " which will explore black holes, " Icy Planets, " another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, " Prism, " a mission to measure cosmic background radiation, and Exoplanet Finder to detect and investigate earth-like planets.
Progposals for the return transport of samples from Mars, for research into the moon, venus and asteroids, as well as solar physics have already been dropped.
