George Kerevan: European Unbundling gives the Scots
A new day, a new story of horrors for independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
This is the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed wire border along the Hadrian Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde proposal highlighted the potential economic benefits that greater freedom to travel in the rest of Europe, but, as expected, this did not matter in the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more favourable to them.
As Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued disregard for Brussels would be only a small concession in exchange for what it really want from the Scots.
So no story.
And one that has come over the years that it already resembles a fossil: the first time I heard the ‘ independence means passport controls ’ duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why should we expect an independent Scotland to dance to the European tune?
Why trade the London yoke for Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the European project officially died.
Parties across the EU that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Euroskeptic Alternative for Germany – founded only this year – won almost five million votes in the September federal election, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
But the current economic crisis is proving to be a turning point.
Many people believe that the European project has gone too far because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket into which their national economies are forced by adherence to the single currency.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments creating excessive budget deficits – only in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members at exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – and that is what German politicians would like.
Without the possibility of devaluing the local currency, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage vis-à-vis Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the “ green ” energy directives imposed by Brussels – a code to subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times for gas as the United States.
This is a paralysing disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All wage in the world do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being marginalised by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt, especially in France, the EU ’ s former cheerleader.
After the war, France ’ s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle for keeping Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and has imposed Europe ’ s own economic policies, which is what the battered French economy is struggling with.
As a result, Marine Le Pen ’ s right-wing, anti-EU National Front has just won a decisive afterelection, putting the ruling socialists in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France, with 24% of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a right-wing divide would automatically benefit the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newfound popularity among the working-class white French?
It wants to use next year's EU elections to forge an anti-EU anti-Community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is perfectly possible – then such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I would like to make: in the not-too-distant future, growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more of the “ Europe of (sovereign) nations ” that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may be holding fast to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering itself with the United States.
But Washington ’ s growing interest in the Pacific region suggests that Britain will be alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is all this?
We can decide to be a region of (ultimately) England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can get where.
I suspect Scotland could do very well in a looser European grouping if we retained our own currency.
Cooperation with other similar countries is easier in an unfederal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, and won a spectacular majority in 2011 by rejecting the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Treasury Secretary Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory Lib Dems coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now only to impose austerity by Berlin and Brussels.
