Scientists were able to shed more light on the connection between a dog ’ s swings and its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs waving the tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs it was the left.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said, “ Man is well known that the left and right half of the brain react differently to stimuli that generate positive or negative emotions. ”
Here we tried to look at this for other species.
He also noticed that in dogs, just as in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the left movement, and vice versa, and that the two hemisphes played different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the side angle of their fellow species, researchers supervised the animals while watched these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of four-legged and analyzed behavior.
We will probably soon understand why the tail is moving in one direction or the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “ We have shown dogs films with dogs – either a faithful version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we have been able to steer the movement of the tail more to the left or to the right. ”
When the animals saw an otherwise expressive dog moving the tail to the right (from the perspective of the waving dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail inclination was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog that wander), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not deliberately communicate with each other through these movements.
He is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience which movements they should and should not worry about.
He said: “ If you have different encounters with other dogs and swaling with the tail in one direction is more linked to friendly behaviour and the right tends to produce less friendly behaviour, you react on the basis of these experiences. ”
Researchers say that the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animal.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behaviour and guest Fellow at the Faculty of Veterinary medicine at the University of Bristol, said that this was not the first study to examine whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog and right when they are a satisfied dog.
Another research at the University of Victoria in Canada said, “ Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog if his tail wings left, not right rather than restless – the other way around than in the Italian study. ”
According to him, the differences could come from the fact that, in the various studies the dogs did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
“ While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain halves are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception, ” Bradshaw said.
However, since their behaviour can easily be recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
