His father and so many of his compatriots suffer in Bwelle mature decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team carried out 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME that travels to rural areas at weekends free medical care.
Since 2008 he and his voluntary group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people forced themselves into minibuses and use the medical equipment on the roof across unpaved terrain to villages in need of help.
Not everything always goes smoothly.
